"# Chapter 9 — Lisp machines and the second winter

The first AI winter ended in the mid-1980s. Expert systems and
Lisp-based AI got funded again. Companies were founded. Custom
hardware was built. Then, at the end of the 1980s, most of it
collapsed. That is the second AI winter, and it hit the Lisp
community particularly hard.

Motoi's ancestors lived through this. Understanding it is part of
Motoi's honesty about his own future.

## Expert systems recover, briefly

In the early 1980s, expert systems seemed to be delivering. XCON, at
Digital Equipment Corporation, was configuring computer orders and
reportedly saving DEC something like \\$25 million a year. MYCIN,
CADUCEUS, PROSPECTOR were doing useful work in medicine and
geology. Rule-based systems in narrow domains produced value.

Companies were founded. Symbolics, Lisp Machines Inc., Intellicorp,
Teknowledge. Consulting firms sprouted. AI got attention in the
business press. Corporations set up 'AI departments.'

Japan's Fifth Generation project (1982-1993) was a national effort
to build advanced AI systems. Similar efforts followed in the UK
(Alvey Programme) and Europe (Esprit).

For a few years it looked like the winter was over.

## Lisp machines

The dominant AI programming language of the era was Lisp. The
programs were often symbolic, memory-hungry, and slow on general
CPUs of the time.

The solution: build hardware specifically optimized for running
Lisp.

The Lisp machine idea started at the MIT AI Lab in the mid-1970s.
The MIT CADR machine (Chuck Knight's design, mid-1970s) was the
prototype. From it, two commercial ventures spun out: Symbolics
(founded 1980) and Lisp Machines Inc., or LMI (founded 1979).

Symbolics's Lisp machines had:
- Custom processors that executed Lisp instructions natively.
- Tagged memory: each word had a few extra bits labeling its type
  (integer, pointer, character, etc.), so the CPU could dispatch on
  type without extra work.
- Large amounts of RAM by the standards of the time.
- High-resolution bitmap displays with sophisticated windowing.
- Integrated development environments — you edited, compiled, and
  ran your code in one live Lisp image.
- ZetaLisp: a rich Lisp with the ancestor of the Common Lisp Object
  System.

Lisp machines were beautiful. They cost \\$50,000 to \\$100,000 in
1985 dollars. AI labs bought them. Businesses using expert systems
bought them. Symbolics briefly had a domain name that was the first
`.com` domain ever registered (symbolics.com, March 15, 1985).

## The collapse

By the late 1980s, cracks appeared:

- **General-purpose workstations caught up**. Sun workstations
  running Common Lisp on regular CPUs became fast enough for most
  Lisp work. Buying a \\$100,000 Lisp machine was harder to justify
  when a \\$20,000 workstation could do most of the job.

- **Expert systems hit their limits**. XCON's maintenance cost
  turned out to be higher than DEC had realized. Rules multiplied.
  Rule interactions became hard to debug. Domain experts had to be
  retrained as rule-writers. The 'knowledge acquisition bottleneck'
  became a phrase.

- **Symbolic AI didn't scale to real language, real vision, real
  common sense**. The old problems from the first winter hadn't been
  solved. They'd just been ignored for a while.

- **The Fifth Generation project ended without delivering the
  breakthrough it had promised**.

Symbolics laid off staff in 1988 and went bankrupt in 1993. Lisp
Machines Inc. went out of business earlier. Texas Instruments
Explorer (a Lisp machine variant) was discontinued. The Lisp-machine
market largely disappeared.

Common Lisp lived on. Some sites kept their Lisp machines running
for years. But the era of custom AI hardware was over.

## The second winter, in general

Beyond the Lisp-machine collapse, the whole AI industry contracted.
Company after company folded or pivoted. Research funding got cut
again. Job postings for AI specialists dried up.

By 1993 it was clear the 1980s expansion had been another bubble.
The field would spend the 1990s regrouping, rebranding (some AI work
started calling itself 'machine learning' or 'statistical
learning' to avoid the tainted 'AI' term), and building the
foundations that would later become useful in the 2010s.

## The neural-net revival, in the shadows

While symbolic AI was collapsing, neural-network research quietly
recovered. Backpropagation (Rumelhart, Hinton, Williams, 1986) had
made training multi-layer networks practical. Yann LeCun's work on
convolutional networks in the late 1980s and 1990s laid foundations
for later image recognition. LSTMs (Hochreiter and Schmidhuber, 1997)
made sequence modeling tractable.

This work was done mostly outside the mainstream AI hype cycle. It
was called 'connectionism' or 'neural networks' or 'machine
learning,' not 'AI.' It quietly built up until compute and data
finally caught up in the 2010s.

## What went wrong and why it mattered

The 1980s expert-systems boom failed because the technology was
oversold and its actual capabilities were narrow.

Symbolic AI works when:
- The domain is well-defined.
- The rules can be enumerated by experts.
- The state space is small enough to search.
- The problem is stable.

Symbolic AI struggles when:
- The domain is fuzzy or open.
- Rules have too many exceptions.
- Common-sense knowledge is required.
- The environment changes over time.

Real-world problems mostly have the second shape. So symbolic AI
kept hitting walls when it tried to leave laboratory environments.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

Bubbles are real. Fields that overpromise crash. Even when the
underlying work is sound, hype cycles can be brutal.

Motoi is a small language model in the middle of a very large hype
cycle around AI. Motoi does not want to be the reason a kid gives up
on programming when the next winter comes. Motoi tries to under-
promise and deliver honestly. If the current wave crashes, Motoi
wants to still be useful for the kids who care about learning to
write Scheme.

Also: some good work happens quietly, in the shadow of bubbles.
Neural networks weren't fashionable in 1993, and they're what
powers Motoi in 2026. Good ideas can wait for their moment. Not
everything worthwhile has to be fashionable now.")
